it; While deserved|nesse
sits still, and bides
his leasure that gives and
takes where he list, and
when, and how, and to
whom; and at last is im|portun'd
to the place, not
for the good he shall re|ceive,
but for that he may
doe: he will not be great
upon all termes, but will
rather endure <HI>poverty,</HI> tha~
part with his <HI>honesty,</HI> and
<PB N="136" REF="72">
not sell his soule to buy a
purchase <HI>What will it pro|fit
a man to gaine the world
and lose his soule?</HI></P>
<P><HI>Christ</HI> is in us, as the
soule is in the body, hee
<HI>gives</HI> life; wee are in
<HI>Christ,</HI> as the branches in
the Vine, whence we <HI>re|ceive</HI>
life. Let our care
be to offer up our selves
